Sure, if you want to move everything to the footer and remove the header entirely, you can adjust your document's layout accordingly. Here’s a basic example of how to do this:

### HTML Structure:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Your Page Title</title>
    <!-- Add your CSS and other head elements here if needed -->
</head>
<body>

<!-- Your main content goes here -->

<footer>
    <!-- Everything you want in the footer goes here -->
    <div class="footer-content">
        <p>Some text for the footer.</p>
        <nav>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">About Us</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </div>
    <!-- Additional footer elements -->
</footer>

<!-- Add your JavaScript and other body elements here if needed -->

</body>
</html>
```

### CSS:
```css
/* Make sure the footer sticks to the bottom of the page */
html, body {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    height: 100%;
}

body > footer {
    position: fixed;
    left: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 100%;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    text-align: center;
}

.footer-content {
    padding: 20px;
}
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The `<footer>` tag is placed at the end of the body content. You can move all your desired footer content inside this tag.
- **CSS**: This CSS ensures that the footer stays at the bottom of the page, covering any existing content in its place if necessary.

You may need to adjust the styling and positioning based on your specific requirements and design needs.

If you have a more complex layout or additional elements you want to move into the footer, please provide more details so I can assist further.
